{"add":{"doc":{"id":"6698fe3549f08d67cb744e26be175fdcce0862004af2838761c3025f1f28c2e0","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Vlada_RH.jpg/220px-Vlada_RH.jpg","previous":[],"after":["The Republic of Croatia is a unitary state using a parliamentary system of governance. With the collapse of the ruling communist party in SFR Yugoslavia, Croatia adopted its present constitution in 1990 and organised its first multi-party elections.[86] It declared independence on 8 October 1991 leading to the break-up of Yugoslavia and the country was internationally recognised by the United Nations in 1992.[72][77] Under its 1990 constitution, Croatia operated a semi-presidential system until 2000 when it switched to a parliamentary system.[87] Government powers in Croatia are divided into legislative, executive and judiciary powers.[88] The legal system of Croatia is civil law, strongly influenced, as is the institutional framework, by the legal heritage of Austria-Hungary.[89] By the time EU accession negotiations were completed on 30 June 2010, Croatian legislation was fully harmonised with the Community acquis.[90]"]}}}